To determine which equation is correct, we need to recall Maxwell's equations for electromagnetism.

Maxwell's equations include:

- Gauss' law for electric field ($E$): 
$\nabla E = \rho / \varepsilon_0$

- Gauss' law for magnetic field (B):
$\nabla B = 0$

- Faraday's law:
$\nabla\times E=-\partial_t B$

- Ampere-Maxwell's law:
$\nabla\times H=J+\partial_tE$

We can use these laws to derive a wave equation that describes how electromagnetic waves propagate through space. 

Firstly, let us start with Faraday's law.
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla\times E&=-\partial_t B\\
\end{aligned}$$

Now taking curl on both sides,
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla(\nabla\times E)&=\nabla(-\partial_t B)
\end{aligned}$$

Using vector identity $$\nabla (\nabla \times A)=\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot A)-\nabla^2A,$$we get,

$$\begin{aligned}
-\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot E)+\nabla ^2 E &= -\nabla( \partial _t B ) \\
-\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot E)+\nabla ^2 E &=-\partial _t ( \nabla B )
\end{aligned}$$

Since $\nabla B = 0$ from Gauss' law for magnetic fields, then this reduces to

$$\begin{aligned}
-\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot E)+\nabla ^2 E &= 0
\end{aligned}$$(This result also follows directly if you apply it to the other two Maxwell’s equations.)

Next consider Ampère-Maxwell's law:
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times H&= J +\partial_tE
\end{aligned}$$Taking the curl again gives
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla(\nabla \times H)&=(\nabla \times J)+\partial_t(\nabla \times E).
\end{aligned}$$Again using our first vector identity above yields
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot H)-\nabla^2H&=(\nabla \times J)+\partial_t(\nabla \times E)
\end{aligned}$$But since there is no free charge density or current so $\nabla \cdot J=0.$ Also because $\nabla \times J=0$ as well due to absence of any net rotation of charges within the region under consideration. Therefore, we have
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot H)-\nabla^2H&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)
\end{aligned}$$From here, we will make some assumptions about the nature of the medium. We assume that the material has constant permittivity $(\varepsilon)$ and permeability $(\mu).$ Then we know that $D=\varepsilon E$ and $B=\mu H.$ Substituting into the previous expression, we obtain
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot D/\varepsilon)-\nabla^2(D/\varepsilon)&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)/\mu
\end{aligned}$$Multiplying each term by $\mu\varepsilon$ results in
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot D)-\mu\varepsilon\nabla^2D&amp;=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Substitute back in $D=\varepsilon E$ to find
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-\mu\varepsilon\nabla^2(\varepsilon E)&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Simplifying further leads to
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-\varepsilon\mu\nabla^2(\varepsilon E)&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Applying another vector identity, we arrive at
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-\nabla^2(\varepsilon E)-\varepsilon\mu\nabla^2(\varepsilon E)&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Combining like terms, we now have
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-(1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla^2(\varepsilon E)&=\partial_t(\nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$If we take the divergence of the last equation, we get
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-\nabla \cdot ((1+ \varepsilon\mu)(\nabla^2(\varepsilon E))&=\nabla \cdot (\partial_t(\nabla \times E))\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Because $\nabla \cdot (\nabla f)=\Delta f$ where $\Delta$ denotes Laplace operator, we simplify the left-hand side to
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-(1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)&=\nabla \cdot (\partial_t(\nabla \times E))\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$By definition of the derivative of cross product, we see that $\nabla \cdot (\partial_t(\nabla \times E))=\partial_{tt}\nabla \times E.$ Thus, we rewrite the right hand side as
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-(1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)&=\partial_{tt}( \nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Recall that $\nabla \times E=-\partial _{ t } B .$ So substituting this value in the previous equation, we get
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)-(1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)&=-\partial_{ tt }( \nabla \times E)\varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Rearranging the order of derivatives, we finally get
$$\begin{aligned}
-(1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)+\nabla^2(\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)&=-\partial_{ tt }\left( \nabla \times E\right) \varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Factoring out common factor of $\nabla ^{2},$ we write
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2}((1+ \varepsilon\mu)\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E-\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E)&=-\partial_{ tt }\left( \nabla \times E\right) \varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$Let $u=\nabla \cdot \varepsilon E$ be the potential function associated with the quantity inside the parentheses. The resulting differential equation becomes
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} u&=-\partial_{ tt }\left( \nabla \times E\right) \varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$However, note that $\nabla \times E=-\partial _{ t } B .$ Hence, we may substitute this relationship into the previous equation to yield
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} u&=-\partial_{ tt }\left( -\partial _{ t } B \right) \varepsilon /\mu \\&=\partial_{ tt } B \varepsilon /\mu .
\end{aligned}$$Therefore, we conclude that
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} u&=\partial_{ tt } B \varepsilon /\mu
\end{aligned}$$In general, when dealing with time-dependent phenomena such as those described by the preceding partial differential equation, one often uses the notation $f(t,x,y,z)$ instead of just $f(x,y,z),$ indicating that the variable $x$ depends not only upon position but also upon time. In particular, we shall denote the second-order partial derivative of $f$ with respect to $t$ by $f_{ tt },$ i.e., $f_{ tt }=\partial _{ tt } f.$ Using this convention, we re-write the equation above as
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} u&=f_{ tt }
\end{aligned}$$where $f=B.$ This is known as the **wave equation**. It states that the rate of change of the square of the magnitude of the magnetic induction over twice the speed of propagation squared equals the negative gradient of the scalar potential times the dielectricity per unit volume divided by the permeability per unit volume.

For simplicity, let us set $u=u(r,t), r=x,y,z$ and expand the Laplacian operator accordingly. Since $u$ does not depend explicitly on $y$ or $z,$ we have
$$\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} u&=\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial x^{2 }}+\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial y^{2 }}+\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial z^{2 }}
\end{aligned}$$Thus, the wave equation takes the form
$$\begin{aligned}
\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial x^{2 }}+\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial y^{2 }}+\frac {\partial ^{2} u}{\partial z^{2 }}&=f_{ tt }
\end{aligned}$$or equivalently
$$\begin{aligned}
\triangle u=f_{ tt },
\end{aligned}$$where $\triangle$ represents the three-dimensional Laplacian operator defined previously. To solve this PDE, we look for solutions of the following type
$$\begin{aligned}
u=g(k,r-t),
\end{aligned}$$where $g$ is an arbitrary differentiable function of its argument. Plugging this guess into the original PDE, we get
$$\begin{aligned}
-g''(k,r-t)-kg'(k,r-t)&=f_{ tt }
\end{aligned}$$Differentiating once more with respect to $t$ and setting $t=r$ yields
$$\begin{aligned}
-k^{2} g(k,r)&=f_{ tt }
\end{aligned}$$which implies that
$$\begin{aligned}
g(k,r)&=\frac {f_{ tt }(kr)}{-k^{2}}
\end{aligned}$$Plugging this result back into the assumed solution, we find
$$\begin{aligned}
u(g,k,r)&=\frac {-f_{ tt }(kr)}{k^{2}}
\end{aligned}$$As before, we replace $f$ with $B$ to obtain
$$\begin{aligned}
u(B,k,r)&=\frac {-B_{ tt }(kr)}{k^{2}}
\end{aligned}$$Finally, plugging this result back into the assumed solution, we find
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=\int d k e^{-ikr}\frac {-B_{ tt }(kr)}{k^{2}}
\end{aligned}$$Note that we used integration rather than summation because we do not specify whether the integral should be taken over all values of $k$ or else. However, we must keep in mind that the latter case would require additional analysis to ensure convergence of the series. Now, we want to express the solution in terms of real quantities. Recall that complex exponentials can be written as sines and cosines via Euler's formula. Specifically, we have
$$\begin{aligned}
e^{i\theta}&=\cos \theta+i\sin \theta ,\\
e^{-i\theta}&=\cos \theta-i\sin \theta ,
\end{aligned}$$so that
$$\begin{aligned}
e^{ix}-e^{-ix}=2i\sin x,\quad e^{iy}-e^{-iy}=2i\sin y,\quad e^{iz}-e^{-iz}=2i\sin z.
\end{aligned}$$These identities allow us to convert the integrals involving complex exponents into sums of sine functions. For example, we have
$$\begin{aligned}
\sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }e^{inx}&=\sum _{ m =-\infty }^{\infty }\delta (m-n)e^{imx}\\
&=\sum _{ m =-\infty }^{\infty }\delta (m-n)e^{ imx}.
\end{aligned}$$Similarly, we can show that
$$\begin{aligned}
\sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-inx}&=\sum _{ m =-\infty }^{\infty }\delta (m+n)e^{- imx},
\end{aligned}$$and thus
$$\begin{aligned}
\sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }[e^{inx}-e^{-inx}]&=\sum _{ m =-\infty }^{\infty }[(\delta (m-n)-\delta(m+n)]e^{ imx}.\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }[e^{inx}-e^{-inx}]&=\sum _{ m =-\infty }^{\infty }[-2i\delta (m+n)]e^{ imx}.
\end{aligned}$$Consequently, we can write
$$\begin{aligned}
\sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }e^{inkx}&=\pi [\delta (k-x)+\delta (k+x)],\\
\sum _{ n =-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-inkx}&=\pi [-\delta (-k-x)+\delta (-k+x)],
\end{aligned}$$for $k>0.$ Note that the summands vanish whenever either index exceeds zero. Applying this fact to the earlier integral, we find
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=\int dk\frac {-B_{ tt }(kr)}{k^{2}}\left [e^{-ikr}-e^{ ik r}\right ]\\
&=\int dk\frac {-B_{ tt }(kr)}{k^{2}}\left [\pi \delta (k-r)+\pi \delta (k+r)\right ]
\end{aligned}$$Integrating the delta functions against their respective test functions, we get
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=-\pi \int dk\frac {[kB_{ tt }(kr)]}{k^{2}}\delta (k-r)-\pi \int dk\frac {[kB_{ tt }(kr)]}{k^{2}}\delta (k+r)\\
&=-\pi \lim _{a\rightarrow 0}[kB_{ tt }(ka)][\Theta (ar-r)]/k^{2})-\pi \lim _{b\to 0}[kB_{ tt }(kb)][\Theta (br+r)]
\end{aligned}$$Here, $\Theta$ stands for Heaviside theta-function. As usual, we interpret the limits as being approached from below. Because $B_{ tt }(kr)$ vanishes faster than linearly as $| kr |\rightarrow \pm \infty ,$ we can safely move the limit past the differentiation operation. After doing so, we find
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=-\pi \lim _{a\rightarrow 0}\left [B_{ tt }(ra)[\Theta (ar-r)]/a\right ]-\pi \lim _{b\to 0}\left [B_{ tt }(rb)[\Theta (br+r)\right ]\\
&=-\pi \lim _{a\rightarrow 0}\left [B_{ tt }(ra)\right ]-\pi \lim _{b\to 0}\left [B_{ tt }(rb)\right ],
\end{aligned}$$because the arguments of the Heaviside theta-functions become positive as soon as $a<0,b>0.$ Finally, recalling that $B_{ tt }=B_{ xx }$ and letting $a=b=0,$ we deduce that
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=-\pi B_{xx}(rt).
\end{aligned}$$So far, we've found that the solution to the wave equation is given by
$$\begin{aligned}
u(r,t)&=-\pi B_{xx}(rt).
\end{aligned}$$It remains to verify that this satisfies the initial conditions imposed on the problem. First, observe that
$$\begin{aligned}
